{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:16:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:16:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16894"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16894"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0,0.05,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76329"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9584"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61838"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5102"},{"type":"tags","id":"10025"},{"type":"tags","id":"10067"},{"type":"tags","id":"10068"},{"type":"tags","id":"10138"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22622"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76329"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucagon is a peptide hormone that plays a crucial role in glucose homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of glucagon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Promotes hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis","Stimulates glucose uptake in adipose tissue","Promotes glycogen synthesis in muscle","Decreases insulin secretion from beta cells","Inhibits protein breakdown in skeletal muscle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of glucagon is to \u003Cstrong\u003Epromote hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E. When blood glucose levels fall, pancreatic alpha cells release glucagon. In the liver, glucagon binds to G-protein coupled receptors, increasing intracellular cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP). This triggers enzymatic cascades that break down glycogen and promote glucose production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreases insulin secretion from beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E: while glucagon and insulin have opposing actions, glucagon does not directly suppress insulin secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes glycogen synthesis in muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: glucagon promotes glycogen breakdown, not synthesis, and primarily acts on the liver rather than muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates glucose uptake in adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E: glucagon promotes glucose release from the liver, not uptake into peripheral tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits protein breakdown in skeletal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E: glucagon actually promotes protein catabolism during periods of prolonged fasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe net effect of glucagon is to increase blood glucose concentration through mobilisation of glucose from hepatic stores by glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucagon primarily increases blood glucose by promoting glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis in the liver.","Glucagon is secreted by pancreatic alpha cells in response to low blood glucose levels.","Glucagon acts through G-protein coupled receptors to increase cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) in hepatocytes."],"references":["Morris CH, Baker J. Glucagon. [Updated 2024 Feb 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559195/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61838"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16894"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61838"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T08:10:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T08:11:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9584"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76329"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount